You can use [`ClassesShould.accessClassesThat()`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.tngtech.archunit/archunit/latest/com/tngtech/archunit/lang/syntax/elements/ClassesShould.html#accessClassesThat()), which (as its JavaDoc suggests) _usually makes more sense the negated way:_
```java
import static com.tngtech.archunit.lang.syntax.ArchRuleDefinition.noClasses;
// ...

  noClasses()
      .that().resideInAPackage(&quot;..controller..&quot;)
      .should().accessClassesThat().resideInAPackage(&quot;..core..&quot;);
```

You can also stick to `classes()` and use [`GivenClasses.should(…)`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.tngtech.archunit/archunit/latest/com/tngtech/archunit/lang/syntax/elements/GivenClasses.html#should(com.tngtech.archunit.lang.ArchCondition)) or [`GivenClassesConjunction.should(…)`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.tngtech.archunit/archunit/latest/com/tngtech/archunit/lang/syntax/elements/GivenClassesConjunction.html#should(com.tngtech.archunit.lang.ArchCondition)) with a flexible  [`ArchCondition`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.tngtech.archunit/archunit/latest/com/tngtech/archunit/lang/ArchCondition.html). For your case, it can be easily composed from pre-defined conditions and [predicates](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.tngtech.archunit/archunit/latest/com/tngtech/archunit/base/DescribedPredicate.html):

```java
import static com.tngtech.archunit.core.domain.JavaClass.Predicates.resideInAPackage;
import static com.tngtech.archunit.lang.conditions.ArchConditions.accessClassesThat;
import static com.tngtech.archunit.lang.conditions.ArchConditions.not;
import static com.tngtech.archunit.lang.syntax.ArchRuleDefinition.classes;
// ...

    classes()
        .that().resideInAPackage(&quot;..controller..&quot;)
        .should(not(accessClassesThat(resideInAPackage(&quot;..core..&quot;))));
```

